article.description: Ticha Penicheiro scored eight points in the final 2:07, and the Sacramento Monarchs held off the Detroit Shock for a 85-75 victory Saturday night in a rematch of the WNBA finals.
article.headline: Penicheiro heats up in fourth quarter as Monarchs top Shock
article.linkText: Penicheiro's scoring punch lifts Monarchs to win
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- Opponents have been daring Ticha Penicheiro to shoot for just about a decade now, from her rookie season in Sacramento to last summer's WNBA Finals.

The Monarchs' shooting-shy guard loved the spotlight Saturday night.

Penicheiro scored eight points in the final 2:07, and Sacramento held off the Detroit Shock for a 85-75 victory in a finals rematch between the WNBA's conference leaders again this season.

With two jumpers, two free throws and a layup, Penicheiro finished off the Monarchs' first win over the Shock since blowing the last two games of last September's finals, when Detroit repeatedly dared Penicheiro to beat them.

"To beat a team like that, it gets rid of some of the bad memories," Penicheiro said. "They beat us here in [Game 4] when we could have won the championship, so we felt like we had to earn their respect again."

She picked an unlikely way to do it. The Portuguese point guard is the league's career assists leader, but her shot is notoriously -- sometimes comically -- erratic for a player who has spent nearly every month of her adult life on a basketball team.

When Penicheiro stepped up, the Shock had nearly erased a 16-point second-half deficit. Katie Smith, who scored 17 points for Detroit, hit a 3-pointer with 2:27 to play to trim the Monarchs' lead to 74-73.

But Penicheiro, who finished with 12 points, hit a long jumper when the Shock purposely left her unguarded. After Nicole Powell hit a free throw, Penicheiro came off a screen and hit another wide-open shot with 1:10 to play, putting Sacramento up 79-73.

Penicheiro added two free throws with 28 seconds left, then hit a breakaway layup moments later.

"T has been working on her shot, and I think the impetus for that was the Detroit series last year," Kara Lawson said. "It's not like she can't shoot at all. It's just about getting the ball where she's comfortable."

Sacramento won for the fourth time in five games, while Detroit (10-2) finished its four-game road trip with its first loss away from home this season.

"They're the best team in the league, and their record shows it," Lawson said. "To be able to beat them shows we're in the place we need to be."

Deanna Nolan scored a season-high 23 points for Detroit, which claimed the five-game finals last season with a stunning victory in Game 4 at Arco Arena to avoid elimination. With Saturday's victory, the Monarchs (9-4) split the season series with Detroit -- and neither team would be surprised if another finals meeting is in their futures.

"If we see them again, it'll be in the finals, so we don't have any worries about what they're doing," Smith said. "They made enough plays at the end to win the game. We needed to play smarter and harder."

Coach Bill Laimbeer bemoaned the Shock's 28-21 foul disparity, as well as Sacramento's 37 free throws to Detroit's 16. Cheryl Ford sat out for the fourth time in Detroit's last five games with a sprained left knee.

"We made crucial mistakes on defense, and they made some big shots at the end," Laimbeer said. "We missed Cheryl Ford. Their offensive rebounding hurt us. We're a little small."

Scholanda Robinson scored a season-high 13 points and Rebekkah Brunson added 11 points and 10 rebounds for the Monarchs. Yolanda Griffith also scored 11 points for Sacramento, which lost its season opener in Detroit.

Both teams played draining road games Friday night, with Sacramento losing in double overtime in Los Angeles while Detroit was working on a comeback victory in Phoenix.

Lawson provided the half's biggest highlight when she leaped to swat rookie Ivory Latta's 3-point attempt into the stands 1.2 seconds before halftime. Lawson then posed with her hands on her hips while Kings players Kevin Martin, Ron Artest and Francisco Garcia laughed and cheered.
